WEBVTT

00:01.820 --> 00:02.180
Okay. Because of personality defects, a few 
people didn't get along very well with them. And

00:08.690 --> 00:19.464
interestingly enough, the Venezuelan officers 
pretty much expected perfection from us,

00:08.690 --> 00:19.464
although they'd accept less for themselves. I 
thought that was an interesting relationship.

00:26.525 --> 00:36.599
If you really applied yourself in trying to help 
them and doing the job you were there to do, they

00:26.525 --> 00:36.599
appreciated it and they respected you for it.

00:38.481 --> 00:45.131
They had the idea that some of the people were there 
to enjoy their life rather than work. But some of

00:45.151 --> 00:46.192
the Americans were. Some of the Americans, but 
that's not really true. What really happened,

00:48.295 --> 00:52.060
this personality thing worked both ways, but 
There were a few cases in which Venezuelan

00:53.660 --> 01:00.890
commanders simply didn't want this advisor 
around for whatever reason. And so they became

01:03.374 --> 01:09.883
ineffective because they weren't accepted, not 
because of personality or anything of the sort.

01:09.923 --> 01:16.453
They just didn't want that advice or help or 
interference, however they looked upon it. And it

01:16.473 --> 01:20.038
was easy to be put in a position of interference.

01:25.807 --> 01:34.200
you know, tried not to distinguish, and that 
almost got me in trouble one time, but basically I

01:25.807 --> 01:34.200
think it was sound. Okay, will you tell me about 
that one time? Well, I would just say very briefly

01:37.405 --> 01:52.388
that, yes, I won't go into detail, but in my core, in 
the course of my learning Spanish, I also picked up

01:37.405 --> 01:52.388
colloquialisms,

01:37.405 --> 01:52.388
and It's interesting that in Spanish, and I 
suppose this to some degree is true in English, but

01:52.587 --> 02:06.659
these colloquialisms mean different things to 
different people depending on what country

01:52.587 --> 02:06.659
you're from. I know Venezuelans who come in to me, 
they were very careful when they went to Mexico of

02:06.799 --> 02:16.608
how they used certain terms because they meant 
different things. Some of them bugger it. And I

02:19.691 --> 02:22.273
also learned after the fact that some of their 
colloquialism used in common, ordinary

02:23.283 --> 02:31.270
conversation under certain circumstances is 
very damaging. And I was guilty of doing that. He

02:35.994 --> 02:51.248
said, he thought, an officer thought that I'd 
insulted him by using such a colloquialism when I

02:35.994 --> 02:51.248
was, appeared to be angry to him, which was under 
such circumstances, if intentional, would have

02:35.994 --> 02:51.248
been an insult. Anyway, he made an official 
complaint that resulted in an investigation

02:52.780 --> 03:04.314
that,

02:52.780 --> 03:04.314
because he'd complained, it had to be reported 
formally. And I was completely exonerated as

03:04.374 --> 03:14.607
having been not at all intentional

03:04.374 --> 03:14.607
in misusing that word. In fact, didn't understand 
it. And to a man, the Venezuelan officers that

03:16.289 --> 03:21.555
testified supported my innocence. And I, of 
course, appreciate that because I think that's a

03:23.619 --> 03:31.070
little bit difficult to do when a foreign 
officer's involved. And it turned out not to be a

03:31.191 --> 03:36.018
big thing, but it did bother me a great deal at the 
time. And it could have been damaging for your

03:37.139 --> 03:39.082
career. It could have been very damaging, as it 
was. I wish I had asked for a copy of that report

03:41.486 --> 03:49.197
because that would have probably been... of more 
value in my file than the efficiency report I got

03:50.324 --> 03:56.510
from my boss, as it were. Because the Venezuelans 
supported you so much. Yeah. Then we left there.

04:02.236 --> 04:06.099
Well, I was wondering, before we leave there, is 
that school still in existence? It is, and as a

04:06.880 --> 04:20.213
matter of fact, my wife and I, Fran and I, were 
invited back ten years later as guests to the

04:06.880 --> 04:20.213
Venezuelan Army to observe the tenth year

04:20.463 --> 04:29.232
observance of the formation of that school.

04:29.392 --> 04:34.017
We were asked to stay for a month, and we stayed, I 
think, ten days. We were just royally treated.

04:36.880 --> 04:38.401
They did have a fine ceremony. Incidentally, 
Lieutenant Colonel Quevedo, who

04:39.422 --> 04:49.913
was the first commandant at this point, was 
commander-in-chief of the Army. of Venezuela.

04:53.352 --> 05:19.275
And interestingly enough,

04:53.352 --> 05:19.275
when Pérez Jiménez, the dictator, was kicked out 
in, I believe it was 1954,

