Coveto was one of the three-man junta that 
reorganized the government, decreed the

04:53.352 --> 05:19.275
Constitutional Convention that set up the 
present government form under the present

05:19.762 --> 05:27.550
Constitution, which provided for two houses of 
Congress, a president serving a five-year tour.

05:27.651 --> 05:38.262
In other words, our basic pattern of the executive 
legislative judicial

05:27.651 --> 05:38.262
got a commitment from the armed forces. The 
Minister of Defense proclaimed that never again

05:38.282 --> 05:47.592
would the Venezuelan armed forces be used against 
the government, only to support the government.

05:49.529 --> 05:56.357
And they're now in their fifth five-year 
presidency without interruption or serious

05:49.529 --> 05:56.357
incident. Incidentally, General Collado became 
a senator. He did? After he retired from the Army in

06:03.745 --> 06:10.914
this system that he helped create. And I consider 
him a patriot. What kind of man is Govedo? Oh, he's a

06:16.371 --> 06:18.354
fine man. He's very likable and very personal.

06:23.881 --> 06:40.883
Just from his physical appearance, and I don't 
know this to be the case, but I would say he's half

06:23.881 --> 06:40.883
Indian, or he's got a lot of Indian blood in him, but 
he's a good native son, and he was a very effective

06:23.881 --> 06:40.883
and popular officer, and obviously able to handle 
the high position of responsibility that he found

06:43.259 --> 06:49.686
himself in as a member of the governing junta. Was 
he from a wealthy family? No. Most of the

06:53.530 --> 06:56.052
Venezuelan officers are not from wealthy 
families. Some are.

06:59.716 --> 07:10.127
Many of them, of course, their social status is 
improved by going through the academy and

06:59.716 --> 07:10.127
becoming an officer.

07:11.373 --> 07:18.823
I went to Venezuela on business a couple of times in 
about 1975 and 1977, I guess it was. On that return

07:20.665 --> 07:27.514
in 1975, I had a wonderful experience of 
recontacting many of these officers. My very best

07:27.574 --> 07:33.602
friend that I made there was Enrique Peña Briseño. 
He was a lieutenant when I arrived in Venezuela,

07:33.662 --> 07:37.347
and he became a general officer. And so we had a good 
reunion there. I'd had a reunion with him in

07:40.232 --> 07:45.340
Washington and Rome in the intervening years. We 
maintained this friendship, he and others. But he

07:48.745 --> 07:50.968
was my best Venezuelan friend. Anyway, most of 
those officers in that first class that I

07:52.671 --> 08:00.924
conducted became general officers. It was 
remarkable.

08:04.563 --> 08:24.969
And as a matter of fact, when I went back there in 75, 
General Cabello was then retired, and he hosted a

08:04.563 --> 08:24.969
reception, cocktail reception, for me, and 
invited all of these people and their wives that he

08:04.563 --> 08:24.969
could get in touch with. And it was just a wonderful 
reunion. Of course, we'd done this on that ten year

08:29.993 --> 08:36.340
anniversary too, so you can see the continuity has 
been maintained rather surprisingly well. Now

08:37.241 --> 08:43.388
there were a couple of events that were very 
important on the international scene when you

08:37.241 --> 08:43.388
were in Venezuela. One was the Korean War. Did you 
want to go to the war? Did you volunteer? No, I

08:47.793 --> 08:50.315
didn't volunteer. I arrived in Venezuela six 
months before that war started.

08:58.968 --> 09:04.154
I left there in 1952 and all of the intensive 
purchases were over. We have in the Army what you

09:04.174 --> 09:09.161
call a stabilized tour. In other words, you're 
sent there and you won't be moved until that tour is

09:09.261 --> 09:13.586
completed. But this was a peculiar one in 
Venezuela. We were under contract with the

09:18.412 --> 09:20.635
Venezuelan Army. As a matter of fact, the 
Venezuelan Army paid me, in addition to my Army

09:21.196 --> 09:27.203
pay, $250,000. $87 a month. What that was was not a 
salary, that was a cost of living differential,

09:32.538 --> 09:43.388
but it was kind of a hold on us, you see, and a 
contract with us. So, I was in effect pinned down

09:43.408 --> 09:50.714
there those three years. Of course, one of the 
major events in recent military history was the

09:51.475 --> 09:58.641
firing of General MacArthur. What did you think of 
Truman's action?

10:03.145 --> 10:10.494
I'm a great admirer of General MacArthur's, and I 
think he's one of the greatest generals we ever

10:03.145 --> 10:10.494
produced. He's one of the greatest strategists 
we've ever produced. I felt President Truman was

10:15.560 --> 10:18.684
correct. He had to do what he did. Very simple. 
After all, he's commander-in-chief. If it had

10:26.212 --> 10:27.514
been MacArthur and him, Lieutenant General down 
below him had been the same thing. Anytime a

10:32.748 --> 10:43.679
subordinate cannot accept the policy direction 
of his superior, he's got to resign or get fired,

10:32.748 --> 10:43.679
one or the other. He got fired.

10:48.383 --> 10:50.545
I never had any question about it, much as I 
regretted it.

10:53.568 --> 10:54.569
Okay. Let's move on now. After this, you went to 
student at the U.S. Command and General Staff

10:56.637 --> 11:03.365
College from August 1952 to July 1953. This is a 
very important event in your career advancement,

11:03.646 --> 11:10.174
isn't it? It is. And that's probably the most 
useful school training that I received in the

11:12.096 --> 11:19.325
Army. And I did attend, of course, the artillery 
school and the war college as well. in some special

11:26.523 --> 11:27.845
schools. But anyway— You thought it was more 
important than the War College? I do, and I'll tell

11:31.191 --> 11:33.375
you why. Good. It was very demanding of time. 
Incidentally, our second child daughter was born

11:36.219 --> 11:39.545
at Leavenworth. Our first child son was born in 
Venezuela.

11:46.577 --> 11:50.383
I thought of that because I had so little time to 
enjoy our baby daughter. I was so busy. Our son, by

11:53.658 --> 12:00.925
the way, had a dual citizenship, and he had to make a 
choice at the age of eighteen, according to

11:53.658 --> 12:00.925
Venezuelan law. And, of course, the choice was 
easy, the choice of citizenship. The Command and

12:07.471 --> 12:21.825
General Staff College prepares officers for 
general staff work at all levels, and it prepares

12:07.471 --> 12:21.825
him for command of units through the division and 
corps. You know, we have the company battalion,

12:28.631 --> 12:41.289
regiment, or brigade, brigade now, division, 
corps, and field army. Well, this brought the

12:41.309 --> 12:48.458
students through the division and corps phase of 
planning and commanding. It was very demanding,

12:50.081 --> 12:52.504
the very because we were always moving at a pace 
that you could never quite finish the race before,

12:53.615 --> 13:03.409
today's race, before the bar starts. And it was 
planned that way. And it's rather disconcerting,

13:05.452 --> 13:11.360
but it's surprising after it's all over how much of 
that exposure you retain. But it was just an

13:11.400 --> 13:16.407
excellent, very best instruction, too, 
quality-wise. But it, I felt, prepared me for just

13:17.669 --> 13:22.035
about any job that I'd be assigned in the Army. It 
gave me a good base to begin any assignment in the

13:23.197 --> 13:31.387
Army. How would you compare that with two years 
later when you went to the Army War College? Well,

13:36.133 --> 13:39.898
it was two assignments later that I went to the Army 
War College. August 1956 to November 1950. Well,

13:41.460 --> 13:50.892
the War College, I think they're very 
complementary, but if I had to choose one as being

13:41.460 --> 13:50.892
the most important, the most valuable to me, it was 
the Command Staff College. The War College, on the

13:51.614 --> 14:02.765
other hand, is the level at which you study 
national strategy and military strategy. So you

14:02.785 --> 14:09.992
see, it complements, it picks up basically where 
the Command Staff College leaves off, and that's

14:02.785 --> 14:09.992
the way it's designed. I thought the experience in 
the

14:11.593 --> 14:17.138
War College was invaluable.

14:19.461 --> 14:20.862
It was the first time since I entered the Army, that 
I and my contemporaries who sat with me there had

14:21.702 --> 14:39.222
the opportunity, the time, and the environment to 
really think policy strategy.

14:43.547 --> 14:50.055
Now, strange as it may seem, if you're on the road 
that far, you're always so, or I was always so

14:50.828 --> 14:57.234
committed to the job that you just had to deal with 
what was at hand, you know. Sure. So it was a

14:58.916 --> 15:00.257
wonderful experience. We used seminars and 
committees and lectures, and there was plenty of

15:00.577 --> 15:14.390
time for individual thought and committee and 
contribution to the committee work. And we'd

15:16.812 --> 15:18.574
treat with a series of, aspects of national and 
military strategy policy and strategy through

15:19.533 --> 15:45.793
the year and so it was just a very fine rounding of uh 
for example i left uh between leavenworth the

15:19.533 --> 15:45.793
command staff college and the war cars i went to the 
pentagon that's my first full tour on the army

15:19.533 --> 15:45.793
staff and i was in a position there to to observe 
this policy and strategy in action because I wound

15:46.634 --> 16:05.120
up as assistant executive officer to the chief 
planning officer of the Army, planning and

15:46.634 --> 16:05.120
operations officer of the Army, the G3, General 
James Gavin at the time I joined that office. And,

16:05.140 --> 16:15.375
of course,

16:05.140 --> 16:15.375
never had in the course of my job to really—and it 
wasn't my position to—to really making my own

16:16.334 --> 16:21.601
judgment on some of these things that were so 
important to the Army and the nation. But when I got

16:21.861 --> 16:27.628
to the War College, then we were told to look at 
these things, and particularly look to the

16:21.861 --> 16:27.628
future. Sure. And make up, get our own 
convictions. You asked me in conversation if I

16:33.235 --> 16:41.526
thought it was practical to have tactical,

16:33.235 --> 16:41.526
use tactical nuclear weapons in war. Mm-hmm. I 
came to the conclusion as a student at War College

16:42.592 --> 16:46.837
that it's going to be done someday. The question 
is, where does this nuclear exchange stop? I can't

16:57.851 --> 17:12.109
see, for example, the U.S. Army in Europe and its 
NATO allies accepting initial defeat by the

16:57.851 --> 17:12.109
Russians should they ever decide to make a 
conventional attack. I can't see them accepting

17:16.607 --> 17:25.896
initial defeat forward and give up East Germany 
because- I mean West Germany. I mean West Germany

17:25.916 --> 17:38.670
because there's no stopping point then once

17:25.916 --> 17:38.670
that West Germany is breached that I can see.

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
think rather than accept such a defeat that we 
would use nuclear weapons which could stop the

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
advance of those forces because of the geography 
and character of the terrain that they've got to

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
come over

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
but at the same time they're then going to bring 
them into play and where does this stop and that is

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
what gives credence to the deterrence of these 
vast nuclear weapons we have that that i say must

17:40.405 --> 18:10.345
never be used So I guess rather than hoping, I'm 
reasoning that we will have effective

18:10.578 --> 18:35.421
deterrents, because it's unthinkable that we 
would let the use of small tactical nuclear

18:10.578 --> 18:35.421
weapons evolve into increasing exchanges that 
wind up with an exchange of thermonuclear

18:10.578 --> 18:35.421
weapons. It's suicide. These are the types of 
issues that you discuss. Those are the types of

18:42.212 --> 18:44.614
issues that we discuss. Plus, for example, at the 
War College. I remember another one. I came to the

18:50.500 --> 18:59.910
conclusion, and each has his own opportunity, you 
know, make his own conclusions, that we should

18:50.500 --> 18:59.910
make our peace with Communist China.

19:03.473 --> 19:07.197
We could not hope to survive a concerted, joint, 
opposition militarily or between China and

19:07.885 --> 19:36.846
Russia against us joint their joint undertaking 
against us they could overrun the vast areas of the

19:07.885 --> 19:36.846
world that are so important to us that it would 
reduce us to to unimportance

19:07.885 --> 19:36.846
but we better see to it that through the United 
Nations or otherwise we get this fester of

19:07.885 --> 19:36.846
hormosis settled And the best way seemed to be to 
get Formosa declared an independent nation with

19:37.653 --> 19:46.242
some name other than China.

19:49.105 --> 19:52.508
Formosa wasn't China before the Communists took 
over. They were a province of China. Chiang

19:58.895 --> 20:03.139
Kai-shek made it China. Well, this never 
happened, so you see where we are now. We have made

20:05.642 --> 20:07.103
our peace with China, but we haven't resolved that 
matter of Formosa, and that will always be a debit

20:07.927 --> 20:17.818
on our account until it's settled.

20:22.843 --> 20:24.865
That's just another example. Let's go to the 
Pentagon. This is the first chance you had to move

20:26.247 --> 20:31.352
into the Pentagon. This is the hub of the military, 
and you moved there in July 1953 and stayed until

20:31.957 --> 20:39.624
August 1956 in two different jobs. Let's describe 
those jobs to begin with. Staff officer,

20:43.066 --> 20:48.331
organization and training division, office of 
assistant chief of staff. Yes. Of course, the

20:50.773 --> 21:01.322
function of the army general staff was to 
establish the policies for the army, promulgate

20:50.773 --> 21:01.322
the policies for the army. do the planning for the 
Army, overall planning, and the budgeting for the

21:02.180 --> 21:13.209
resources of the Army, procurement there of those 
resources. In the training field, which I was in

21:15.211 --> 21:22.537
initially, we basically set training policy in 
that shop. We developed training policy to be

21:22.637 --> 21:28.843
promulgated by the Army Chief of Staff and 
Secretary of the Army. And this had to do with, at

21:28.863 --> 21:31.545
the time, Training sounds like a simple term, and 
it is, because in the course of our career, most of

21:33.263 --> 21:41.512
our time spent training. The interesting thing at 
the time, of course, was training in nuclear

21:41.972 --> 21:45.256
weapons. They were new to us. We still, in 1953, had 
not become accustomed to them, so that was one of

21:48.219 --> 21:58.630
the challenges, nuclear training. Of course, 
this is the time that the American Armed Forces are

21:59.369 --> 22:08.198
still having above-atmosphere bomb testing. 
Were you in any way involved with those tests? I was

22:11.001 --> 22:14.505
involved in the planning for them, yes, but I was 
never on site. Actually, one thing I wanted to do

22:14.585 --> 22:21.212
was to get on site and observe this nuclear weapon. 
I never had the opportunity. Of course, at that

22:24.295 --> 22:28.920
time, now we're reflecting, of course, on the The 
radiation. The radiation that may have been

22:31.686 --> 22:38.296
lasting effects, which are affecting the health 
of people who were there, and I'm sure that more is

22:31.686 --> 22:38.296
going to be learned of that. At the time, safety was 
a very, very important aspect of it, of course, and

22:39.598 --> 22:50.675
the extreme precautions were taken to shield the 
people. And, of course, safety is always primary

22:52.157 --> 22:56.764
in Well, just shooting artillery, for example, 
for practice. But I'm sure that, obviously, we've

23:03.032 --> 23:10.061
learned a lot about them since that we didn't know 
then. Now, I don't know really how to evaluate this

23:10.121 --> 23:23.236
problem because I've never seen the data on what we 
know now versus what we knew then on the

23:10.121 --> 23:23.236
penetration of this radiation. We were just in the 
exploratory phase as far as nuclear weapons and as

23:24.217 --> 23:29.063
far as— We had to learn. We had to learn more about 
this weapon, this family of weapons. And I thought

23:37.683 --> 23:58.543
at the time that these were very

23:37.683 --> 23:58.543
forward actions being taken, you know, and 
courageous in many ways to undertake those tests

23:37.683 --> 23:58.543
like we did to find out more about it. Now, what 
those dangers were, as we look back in retrospect,

23:58.895 --> 24:05.761
we're going to know more about, I'm sure, in short 
order. I believe the state and the legislature and

24:07.843 --> 24:28.041
the federal government have both recently passed 
bills that are going to create the resources to not

24:07.843 --> 24:28.041
only treat the people who've been affected, you 
know, to help them with their problem of

24:07.843 --> 24:28.041
treatment, and the Agent Orange people from 
Vietnam but also to study this more carefully so

24:28.814 --> 24:33.380
that we learn more. Well, in the last few years in 
the news, during the 1970s especially, some

24:34.081 --> 24:48.599
journalists and other commentators have charged 
that the Army was using their troops as guinea

24:34.081 --> 24:48.599
pigs. What's your opinion of those charges?

24:57.991 --> 25:01.315
Why don't we put that into English-specific 
terms? What's a guinea pig? Well, using human

25:02.637 --> 25:10.187
soldiers out there

25:02.637 --> 25:10.187
for experiments. I think that to some extent that 
was true because

25:10.367 --> 25:27.930
we were conducting those tests to see what the 
blast effects were on structures and troops.

25:29.058 --> 25:36.289
military equipment, what the heat effects were, 
what the radiation effects were. And I'm sure that

25:39.013 --> 25:42.598
to some extent that was the purpose of those troops 
being there. The other purpose was that they

25:42.718 --> 25:51.471
become, shall we say, oriented to some degree in 
what this really is.

25:52.784 --> 26:07.080
But the Army felt that it had to start, of course, 
positioning troops at an absolutely safe

25:52.784 --> 26:07.080
distance

25:52.784 --> 26:07.080
to measure the effects and not go closer than would 
be considered safe. Now, I'm sure if what is being

26:07.120 --> 26:15.088
implied that they were deliberately put into 
unsafe areas to see what the effects would be, that

26:07.120 --> 26:15.088
is not true. I think it's entirely possible that 
they were put into a position that was considered

26:16.410 --> 26:22.116
to be safe But the knowledge at the time led him to a 
bad judgment.

26:31.877 --> 26:41.931
What other types of testing besides nuclear, 
because you were an expert in artillery, were you

26:31.877 --> 26:41.931
also in charge of that at the Pentagon? No, being an 
artilleryman had nothing to do with mine. I was a

26:45.636 --> 26:51.985
general staff officer expected to handle any 
subject in my field.

26:56.538 --> 26:58.580
But you ask what else. At that time, of course, we 
were preparing an artillery nuclear weapon. At

27:04.767 --> 27:09.993
that time, we also were developing advanced 
chemical weapons. These are the tedious ones that

27:10.033 --> 27:14.038
come to mind.

27:16.921 --> 27:21.246
How successful were you in these developments?

27:22.981 --> 27:26.846
That's one of the things about serving in the 
Pentagon that is a bit frustrating. What you do

27:27.727 --> 27:44.989
there is seldom,

27:27.727 --> 27:44.989
particularly in the areas of planning and 
strategy, of course, the effects of what you've

27:27.727 --> 27:44.989
done is seldom seen within a matter of the time 
you're there. It's probably after you leave that

27:45.049 --> 27:48.533
the impact is really visible. That's 
particularly true in developments of new things.

27:53.948 --> 28:09.543
For example, I just read this morning in one of my 
military magazines that the field artillery's

27:53.948 --> 28:09.543
computerized fire direction system is now being 
deployed throughout the Army. When I was at Fort

