Selle in 1961 as chief of research and the 
development organization.

28:21.302 --> 28:27.890
We initiated that

28:21.302 --> 28:27.890
research on that specific system. And we 
developed computer programs to try out on

28:29.252 --> 28:35.219
commercial computers, because we didn't have any 
in the Army. And do you know that that was twenty

28:37.142 --> 28:38.964
years ago? Sure. That's an example of how long it 
takes to really realize what you started in

28:39.945 --> 28:45.452
development. It shouldn't have taken that long, I 
might add, and I think it's disgraceful that it

28:46.664 --> 28:51.892
did. And I think the major element in that is 
decision time. Do you think the Pentagon works too

28:58.983 --> 29:02.248
slowly, then? Without question.

29:07.816 --> 29:08.537
Why is that?

29:11.420 --> 29:12.662
I'm not a reactionary. I don't think we could go 
back to the old ways of doing things and do them

29:12.802 --> 29:16.567
better. But some of the principles that applied 
then certainly apply now. If we'd go back to the

29:24.598 --> 29:41.241
year that I entered the Army, 1941, the 
development of that computer system or its

29:24.598 --> 29:41.241
counterpart in those days would have been in the 
province of the chief of field artillery on the

29:24.598 --> 29:41.241
Army staff. And he would have made the basic 
decisions on it. And when he said, I've got

29:45.826 --> 29:52.813
something that's ready, the Chief of Staff of the 
Army and the Secretary of the Army would have made

29:45.826 --> 29:52.813
the final decision on it. And that would entail 
then the proper program, budget, and money to buy

29:53.214 --> 30:00.461
it, develop it and buy it. Today, the Secretary of 
Defense makes that decision. It's ridiculous.

30:06.547 --> 30:11.312
And when you count the Secretary of Defense or his 
deputies, When you count the treatment then of

30:12.338 --> 30:37.620
this problem between the guys at Fort Sill who are 
trying to develop this for the user in the field, or

30:12.338 --> 30:37.620
trying to get the requirements stated and get it 
developed, and count the contacts and the actions

30:12.338 --> 30:37.620
between him now under the present system and the 
Office of the Secretary of Defense, it's

30:12.338 --> 30:37.620
absolutely miraculous that anything ever gets 
out.

30:40.604 --> 30:53.577
It's the most disappointing thing, and by the way, 
we'll get down the line, I was in the development

30:40.604 --> 30:53.577
business as a major general before I went to the 
Pentagon as chief legislative liaison.

30:54.959 --> 30:59.043
And it's one of the most disappointing things in my 
service to see how encumbered we are.

31:02.287 --> 31:07.352
And it's a result of putting the dollar focus first 
on everything. Certainly you can't You can't

31:10.540 --> 31:12.503
ignore the dollar. God knows we can't afford the 
dollars we really need to prepare. But when you put

31:19.111 --> 31:38.757
the decisions on weapons and weapon-supporting 
systems,

31:19.111 --> 31:38.757
materiel, in the hands of civilians, I'm not 
questioning civilian authority, they can only

31:19.111 --> 31:38.757
think in terms of dollars because they don't 
understand the weapon system. Really. Really.

31:40.325 --> 31:43.409
how this is going to be used and what the real need 
is.

31:47.174 --> 32:06.601
And we're going to have to

31:47.174 --> 32:06.601
return to the principle that the user, the guy in 
uniform, has got the loudest voice and what is

31:47.174 --> 32:06.601
going to be produced for him or we're going to be in 
real trouble. We're already in real trouble. Now

32:09.350 --> 32:17.599
I'm critical of some of that CBS program recently 
on national security of the United States, but

32:09.350 --> 32:17.599
they pointed up some of these points. What was the 
difference between your first job from July 53 to

32:19.461 --> 32:32.074
April 54 and then April 54 to August 56 when you were 
shifted to assistant executive officer? What was

32:32.694 --> 32:35.357
the difference in that?

32:42.323 --> 32:43.685
assistant executive officer. Well, it's very 
different. And if you'd like, I'll outline what

32:49.372 --> 32:53.577
the assistant executive officer is. I was 
assistant to the executive officer. The

32:55.699 --> 33:02.948
executive officer was a colonel, and he's the man 
in the office of the assistant chief of staff, G-3.

33:03.289 --> 33:07.334
We had four general officers up there, the G-3 and 
three assistants. And that colonel was the fellow

33:09.830 --> 33:15.759
that they turned to to get this done or bring me this 
kind of advice and so forth. He was really his, you

33:16.219 --> 33:20.425
might say, if you could think of it, his chief of 
staff. The G3's chief of staff. And I was the

33:24.111 --> 33:26.554
assistant chief of staff in those terms. This 
meant that all this whole area of responsibility

33:28.798 --> 33:39.313
of training, operations, plans came to a focus at 
this office.

33:42.787 --> 33:50.895
And therefore,

33:42.787 --> 33:50.895
much of these actions, of course, are handled on 
paper and in specific formats. As a matter of fact,

33:52.236 --> 33:58.562
when a paper is put on one of those generous desks, 
the whole story is on the top sheet in summary. Then

33:58.882 --> 34:00.924
they can get into as much detail as he wants to. Only 
one sheet.

34:05.468 --> 34:08.051
One sheet of paper on the top. So did you do a lot of 
drafting then? No, I did the managing of getting it

34:10.208 --> 34:20.547
done and of getting into the details that they 
didn't want to deal with after they'd seen the

34:10.208 --> 34:20.547
summary. I had to read every one of those papers 
before it went into them. And then if they take

34:25.136 --> 34:34.613
whatever instruction they had with regard to that 
action after they had dealt with it, often I would

34:25.136 --> 34:34.613
take it in and actually present it to them 
verbally. In fact, I say often, that was more the

34:35.909 --> 34:44.678
rule than the exception. This meant that I had to 
prepare myself in that specific topic.

34:51.565 --> 34:59.653
There had been hundreds of staff hours of work, 
staff officers' work, gone into it in many cases

34:51.565 --> 34:59.653
because it's not just the guy preparing it. But he 
has to coordinate it with those who have an

34:59.733 --> 35:05.038
interest in it, not only in G-3 but G1 personnel or 
G2 intelligence or G4 logistics. And I felt a great

35:11.057 --> 35:21.951
responsibility that if I was going to go in there 
and present this for a decision that I understood

35:11.057 --> 35:21.951
it and that I presented it correctly. No general 
can sit there and read every one of these papers

35:23.113 --> 35:30.782
that have all that background behind that top 
sheet. So they'd want a briefing. So they'd want a

35:32.164 --> 35:34.367
briefing and that was the Many of these, of course, 
were very simple. Some of them were very complex

35:37.135 --> 35:39.818
and very important. But I could get so much of this 
out of their way and conserve the time of the staff

35:41.079 --> 35:57.719
officers who worked on it by preparing myself, 
taking in, presenting, and getting a decision,

35:41.079 --> 35:57.719
and I'd write out the decision to go back for 
implementation. I'd write out the decision made

35:57.739 --> 36:04.607
as expressed by the general officer who made the 
decision. Perhaps it was one he made a

36:05.617 --> 36:13.750
recommendation because it had to go on to the Chief 
of Staff, maybe the Secretary of the Army, maybe

36:05.617 --> 36:13.750
the Secretary of Defense, depending. Some even to 
the President occasionally. So anyway, I was just

36:17.876 --> 36:33.160
a flunky, but at the same time I got into the stream 
of information on this and knowledge and

36:17.876 --> 36:33.160
consideration on it by virtue of the fact that I was 
an administrator

36:17.876 --> 36:33.160
who was presenting the problems in many instances 
to the decision-maker. Now, in some of these very

36:36.757 --> 36:56.700
complex cases, it would be clear to me that I should 
not present it because it takes so much

36:36.757 --> 36:56.700
preparation, background, and knowledge on the 
subject that I would simply call the division

36:36.757 --> 36:56.700
chief concerned and request that they present it. 
They present it, having dealt with it, by briefing

37:02.215 --> 37:05.679
to the General and then set it up with the General. 
Now did your opinion of the Pentagon and the

37:05.699 --> 37:18.634
workings of the Pentagon change before you went to 
the Pentagon and while you were there and after you

37:05.699 --> 37:18.634
left? Did my opinion change? Yeah. What did you 
think of how the Army was run?

37:31.055 --> 37:34.818
sort of a parallel to my description of going back 
to A&M on the staff. You know, at a distance you

37:34.838 --> 37:47.610
respect higher authority and don't know the 
details and don't realize that there are some

37:34.838 --> 37:47.610
little fights and fusses and rough spots that you 
never see, but when you're there you see them. But I

37:47.630 --> 37:53.556
was very proud of the effectiveness and 
efficiency of the Army staff. The more I came to

37:53.576 --> 37:58.120
know it, the more I believed in it as a system, and it 
is a system. Sure. that we used was basically

38:01.328 --> 38:05.694
created with the Germans, you know. And it's 
sound. It's been used for years and years. I do

38:09.018 --> 38:30.306
think that

38:09.018 --> 38:30.306
subsequently

38:09.018 --> 38:30.306
we've gotten off to excellence because we don't 
have

38:09.018 --> 38:30.306
a general staff system really anymore. we have the 
whiz kids staff system the McNamara system we'll

38:31.096 --> 39:01.002
get to McNamara we'll give you a full chance it's 
confused the lines of action and staffing

38:31.096 --> 39:01.002
procedures so that well it's what adds these years 
to our getting where we want to go in my opinion now

38:31.096 --> 39:01.002
we'll get to McNamara we're going to talk about him 
he's very important

38:31.096 --> 39:01.002
I've heard that The Pentagon consumes long hours. 
Is that what you found? Indeed. Matter of fact, on

39:06.985 --> 39:17.139
this job I've just described to you, seldom would I 
get out of the— I'd be there early before anybody

39:06.985 --> 39:17.139
had came in that office in the morning. How early? 
Oh, I'd usually be there by 7 or 7.30. And rarely did

39:21.665 --> 39:26.031
I ever get out of there before 7 at night, sometimes 
later. It might be interesting to mention— that

39:31.627 --> 39:44.543
the executive officer to whom I was assistant was 
then Colonel Harold K. Johnson, who became Chief

39:31.627 --> 39:44.543
of Staff of the Army.

39:44.563 --> 39:53.313
So, I had some very good guidance, and he was doing 
the managing, and I was doing the flunky work in

39:44.563 --> 39:53.313
there and keeping that office going. How was he as a 
leader? Tremendous. Tremendous.

40:03.655 --> 40:07.540
if not the most admired man, one of the most in my 
career. He, an interesting thing,

40:09.742 --> 40:32.430
he had one of the most brilliant minds, one of the 
most human personalities, and one of the most

40:09.742 --> 40:32.430
dedicated commitments to service anyone ever 
knew. and very religious. He was a victim of the

40:38.184 --> 40:43.289
death march at the time. He was a prisoner of the 
Japanese through that whole ordeal, and he was

40:43.309 --> 40:49.974
liberated at the end of the war. He was a very 
corresponding and strong man when he went in, but

40:51.996 --> 41:01.364
he came out stronger in character.

41:01.384 --> 41:03.126
I'm sure he never had an idol moment mentally 
during his captivity because he just maintained

41:03.730 --> 41:33.265
his sharpness and his vision and so well most 
people who went through that ordeal were damaged

41:03.730 --> 41:33.265
to some extent but not him and I've seen others who 
weren't who came out stronger too as a result of

41:03.730 --> 41:33.265
that so anyway he was a he was a fine mentor He

41:33.616 --> 41:39.324
was chief staff during the Vietnam War. Yeah. You 
went from the Pentagon to the Army War College, and

41:40.665 --> 41:58.088
then you went right after that in November 1957 as a 
colonel to the Strategic Intelligence School and

41:40.665 --> 41:58.088
the Language School, in which you stayed for about 
a year and a half until June 1959 before you went to

41:40.665 --> 41:58.088
Yugoslavia. Let's talk about the Intelligence 
School. All right.

42:05.493 --> 42:10.679
At the Army War College, as you're completing your 
year, you get your assignment, your next

42:05.493 --> 42:10.679
assignment. They come up and tell you first before 
they issue the orders. Well, they told me that I had

42:13.281 --> 42:18.707
been selected as military attache to Yugoslavia. 
And I said, I don't want that job. Really? And they

42:21.310 --> 42:22.391
said, well, it's yours. Why? Why didn't you want 
it? Well, in Venezuela, I had observed an attache

42:24.353 --> 42:29.318
at work, and he became a good friend. And he was a 
very pleasant person, and I liked him. I saw

42:32.602 --> 42:33.643
something of him later. But he was military 
attaché to Venezuela, and he was over to our

42:34.720 --> 42:41.950
mission frequently, and I didn't see that he had a 
job to do. As it turns out, that's pretty much true

42:44.494 --> 42:59.956
when you're attaché to an allied country or a very 
friendly country, but it's quite different in a

42:44.494 --> 42:59.956
country that's not that close to us, like 
Yugoslavia being a communist country and so forth

42:44.494 --> 42:59.956
and so on. After all, the primary function of an 
attaché is military intelligence. particularly

43:04.859 --> 43:06.821
strategic intelligence. In other words, the 
things that are going to be important for the long

43:08.303 --> 43:12.768
pull or for the longer range of time. So anyway, I 
just didn't say much about it. Of course, in my

43:18.193 --> 43:31.147
class were people who'd been in personnel and 
intelligence and in attaché duty, and so I went

43:18.193 --> 43:31.147
around asking them, how do I get out of this? Almost 
to a man they said, don't. don't even try. I

43:35.095 --> 43:56.495
thought, really, honestly, and I say I'm naive, 
but I thought that the Army only took volunteers

43:35.095 --> 43:56.495
for military out-of-shade duty because of the 
peculiar aspects

43:35.095 --> 43:56.495
of the—you're attached to an embassy, you see, and 
you're really on diplomatic status, and you're

43:35.095 --> 43:56.495
very heavily committed to a social calendar. 
Sure. Absolutely. And this is the other thing.

43:59.899 --> 44:01.220
That never appealed to me. In fact, that, to me, 
appeared to be a burden and a debilitator. So I

44:09.380 --> 44:26.025
thought, and also in some posts, it used to be, it 
wasn't at this time, it used to be, and this kind of

44:09.380 --> 44:26.025
got into the knowledge of the position, that 
they'd select officers who had additional, you

44:09.380 --> 44:26.025
know, extra income, resources, because they'd 
spend more than they made. Well, that wasn't true

44:26.686 --> 44:32.494
at the time I went on duty because in order to send 
whoever they wanted to, Part of the reason, they

44:32.980 --> 44:39.228
provided the necessary allowances to cover those 
extra expenses. But anyway, they said, don't try

44:39.248 --> 44:41.251
to get out. First of all, you probably can't. 
Secondly, if you try too hard, don't. Or even if you

44:46.377 --> 44:50.162
do succeed, it's going to damage you. It's going to 
damage your record, your assignment probability

44:50.222 --> 44:55.188
for the next assignment. Not that people are going 
to be unfair, but you just declared that you're not

44:56.150 --> 45:01.356
willing to do what you're told to do. You know that 
doesn't fit. So anyway, it took a year and a half to

45:03.743 --> 45:12.633
prepare for that assignment, and that was only a 
two-year assignment. And that seems

45:12.653 --> 45:14.015
extravagant. It sure does. And it is very 
expensive. I bet. And it really, and I recommended

45:17.499 --> 45:25.409
that it be made a three-year assignment to make it 
more cost effective. Now, the reason I didn't

45:25.429 --> 45:32.637
extend is that, strangely enough, when I got on 
post to do my two-year job if I didn't tell them

45:32.870 --> 45:38.416
within a month or so, as I recall, a very short 
period of time. Well, obviously, if it takes a year

45:39.417 --> 45:43.201
and a half to prepare, they've got to know right 
away. I didn't know whether I wanted to extend or

45:43.762 --> 45:45.423
not. And it was a two-year assignment because it 
was not considered a desirable assignment. It

45:50.169 --> 45:55.074
was, you know, rough on the family.

45:55.094 --> 46:00.580
So anyway, that year and a half preparation 
included six months of strategic intelligence

45:55.094 --> 46:00.580
school. In which you studied? In which, uh, We were 
oriented on really what the importance of

46:03.447 --> 46:14.959
strategic intelligence, how it's gathered, how 
it's put together, and what it means to the nation,

46:03.447 --> 46:14.959
to the Army. Where was that school? It was in 
Washington, and that was very valuable. And it

46:19.884 --> 46:28.573
did, of course, have a period of time devoted to 
attache functions and how best to approach those.

46:29.154 --> 46:30.535
You're your own boss, pretty much. you know, 
profiting from the guidelines the Army gives and

46:31.780 --> 46:35.425
the experiences of others. Then I went to the Army 
Language School to study the Yugoslav language,

46:37.228 --> 46:46.282
and that was absolutely essential because 
English is... You just can't get by. You couldn't

46:46.342 --> 46:47.584
then, anyway. You could not get that job done in 
English now. There's just no way to do it. And, of

46:52.892 --> 46:54.254
course, the Army realized that. Well, why do you 
think they picked you for this job? I think the...

46:59.962 --> 47:04.993
The basic reason that I was chosen for that job was 
because of my experience in Venezuela, which was

46:59.962 --> 47:04.993
not without a reason.

